\v 5 \w circumcised|strong="G4061"\w* \w the|strong="G1537"\w* \w eighth|strong="G3637"\w* \w day|strong="G3637"\w*, \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G1537"\w* \w nation|strong="G1085"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w Israel|strong="G2474"\w*, \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G1537"\w* \w tribe|strong="G5443"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* Benjamin, \w a|strong="G1537"\w* \w Hebrew|strong="G1445"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G1537"\w* \w Hebrews|strong="G1445"\w*; \w with|strong="G1537"\w* respect \w to|strong="G2596"\w* \w the|strong="G1537"\w* \w Law|strong="G3551"\w*, \w a|strong="G1537"\w* \w Pharisee|strong="G5330"\w*;  
\v 6 \w with|strong="G1722"\w* respect \w to|strong="G2596"\w* \w zeal|strong="G2205"\w*, \w persecuting|strong="G1377"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Church|strong="G1577"\w*; \w with|strong="G1722"\w* respect \w to|strong="G2596"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w righteousness|strong="G1343"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w law|strong="G3551"\w*, blameless.\f + \fr 3:6 \ft Since Paul did not choose to be born to Hebrew parents, Benjaminites, nor to be circumcised the eighth day, these were advantages of birth. The rest was his choice. He is claiming that if Judaism could save, he was saved.\f*   
\p
\v 7 \w But|strong="G3588"\w* \w such|strong="G3778"\w* \w things|strong="G3778"\w* \w as|strong="G2233"\w* \w were|strong="G1510"\w* \w gain|strong="G2771"\w* \w to|strong="G5547"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*, \w these|strong="G3778"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w have|strong="G1473"\w* \w considered|strong="G2233"\w* \w loss|strong="G2209"\w* \w for|strong="G1223"\w* \w the|strong="G1223"\w* \w sake|strong="G1223"\w* \w of|strong="G1223"\w* \w the|strong="G1223"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w*.  
\v 8 Yes \w indeed|strong="G2532"\w*, \w in|strong="G2532"\w* fact \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w actually|strong="G2532"\w* \w consider|strong="G2233"\w* \w everything|strong="G3956"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w loss|strong="G2209"\w* \w for|strong="G1223"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w sake|strong="G1223"\w* \w of|strong="G1223"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* excelling \w thing|strong="G3956"\w*, \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w knowledge|strong="G1108"\w* \w of|strong="G1223"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w my|strong="G3956"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w*\f + \fr 3:8 \ft The most important thing in this life is to know Jesus Christ as Lord. (One is reminded of the parables of the treasure and the pearl.)\f*—\w for|strong="G1223"\w* \w His|strong="G3956"\w* \w sake|strong="G1223"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* already lost \w everything|strong="G3956"\w*\f + \fr 3:8 \ft Since Paul was born a Roman citizen, his father was wealthy enough to buy that privilege. Had Paul (Saul) remained in Tarsus, he would probably have had an established social position.\f* (\w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w consider|strong="G2233"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w as|strong="G2532"\w* trash), \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w may|strong="G2532"\w* \w gain|strong="G2770"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w*  
\v 9 \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w be|strong="G2532"\w* \w found|strong="G2147"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, \w not|strong="G3361"\w* \w having|strong="G2192"\w* \w as|strong="G1722"\w* \w my|strong="G1699"\w* \w righteousness|strong="G1343"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Law|strong="G3551"\w* \w but|strong="G2532"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w which|strong="G3588"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w through|strong="G1223"\w* \w faith|strong="G4102"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w*, \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w righteousness|strong="G1343"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w based|strong="G1537"\w* \w on|strong="G1909"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w faith|strong="G4102"\w*;  
\v 10 \w so|strong="G2532"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w I|strong="G2532"\w* \w may|strong="G2532"\w* \w know|strong="G1097"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w power|strong="G1411"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w His|strong="G2532"\w* resurrection, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w sharing|strong="G2842"\w* \w in|strong="G2532"\w* \w His|strong="G2532"\w* \w sufferings|strong="G3804"\w*,\f + \fr 3:10 \ft The power of His resurrection is something I would really like to have, but if the price is to share in His sufferings…\f* becoming like \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w in|strong="G2532"\w* \w His|strong="G2532"\w* \w death|strong="G2288"\w*,\f + \fr 3:10 \ft We cannot resurrect if we have not died.\f*  
\v 11 \w and|strong="G3498"\w* \w so|strong="G1519"\w*, \w somehow|strong="G1513"\w*,\f + \fr 3:11 \ft “And so, somehow”—this really does not sound like ‘once saved, always saved’. The writings of the Apostle Paul contain a variety of clear declarations to the effect that God is Sovereign; they equally contain a variety of clear declarations to the effect that we are responsible. In spite of having given up everything for Christ, in spite of being an Apostle, Paul is not resting on his laurels, is not taking anything for granted. He clearly recognizes his own responsibility to “press on”.\f* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w I|strong="G1487"\w* \w may|strong="G1487"\w* arrive \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w resurrection|strong="G1815"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w among|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w dead|strong="G3498"\w*  
